abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value:
Maurice Isserman is an historian and author of 
                <emph render="italic">The Other American: The Life of Michael Harrington</emph> (2000), and several other books relating to the history of the American left. The collection contains interview transcripts, topical files, newspaper clippings by and about Harrington, and FOIA files obtained by Isserman. Prominent interviewees include: William F. Buckley, Lewis Coser, Norman Dorsen, Hal Draper, Harry Fleischman, John K. Galbraith, Herbert Gans, Michael Harrington (there are also two interviews of Harrington conducted by others), his wife Stephanie Harrington, Irving Howe, Irving Kristol, David McReynolds, Jack Newfield, Victor Reuther, Eugene Rostow, Andre Schiffrin, Stanley Sheinbaum, and Diana Trilling.

p.value:
Michael Harrington (1928-1989), is best known as the author of 
                <emph render="italic">The Other America: Poverty in the United States</emph> (1962), and as the founder and leader of the Democratic Socialist Organizing Committee, which later became the Democratic Socialists of America (U.S. affiliate of the Socialist International). He also taught political science at Queens College, part of the City University of New York, and continued to write, lecture and travel widely until his death from cancer in 1989. Among his many books were two autobiographical works, 
                <title render="italic">Taking Sides: The Education of a Militant Mind</title>(1985) and 
                <title render="italic">The Long-Distance Runner : An Autobiography</title>(1987), 
                <title render="italic">The New American Poverty</title>(1984), 
                <title render="italic">The Politics at God's Funeral: The Spiritual Crisis of Western Civilization</title>(1985), and 
                <title render="italic">Socialism : Past and Future</title>(1989).

The collection is organized into four series: I, Interview transcripts; II, Topical files; III, Newspaper clippings; IV, FOIA files. Prominent interviewees include: William F. Buckley, Lewis Coser, Norman Dorsen, Hal Draper, Harry Fleischman, John K. Galbraith, Herbert Gans, Michael Harrington (there are also two interviews of Harrington conducted by others), his wife Stephanie Harrington, Irving Howe, Irving Kristol, David McReynolds, Jack Newfield, Victor Reuther, Eugene Rostow, Andre Schiffrin, Stanley Sheinbaum, and Diana Trilling. The topical files contain background material on people, organizations and issues. The newspaper clippings consist of articles by and about Michael Harrington. The four FOIA files were obtained by Isserman.
